 his eldest son John were passengers on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1621; they were joined two years later by Francis's wife and other children. In the words of William Bradford, he lived long enough ‘to see his children's children have children’."],"variants":[{"name":"Cook","meanings":["English: occupational name for a cook, a seller of cooked meats, or a keeper of an eating house, from Middle English <i>cok</i>, <i>coke</i>, <i>cook</i>, <i>couk</i>, <i>cuk(e)</i> (Old English <i>cōc</i>) ‘cook’ or ‘seller of cooked foods’. See also   Kew  .","Irish and Scottish: usually identical in origin with the English name (see 1 above), but in some cases a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cúg</b> ‘son of Hugo’ (see   McCook  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘cook’, such as German and Jewish   Koch  , Dutch   Kook  , Polish <b>Kucharz</b> and   Kucharczyk  , Slovenian and Croatian   Kuhar  , North German   Kuk  ."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":24,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Alexander Cooke was born in 1200, in Leicester, Leicestershire, England, his father, Albert Cooke, was 21 and his mother, Ann Hook, was 18. He married Lettice Cornelious in 1219, in Leicestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1230, in his hometown, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1200–1230":"1200–1230","1202–Male":"1202–Surnud","1203–1330":"1203–1330","1205–1275":"1205–1275","1203–1245":"1203–1245","1220–1294":"1220–1294","1224–1304":"1224–1304","1226–1357":"1226–1357","1227–1307":"1227–1307","1230–1275":"1230–1275","1179–1210":"1179–1210","1182–1215":"1182–1215","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1330":"1330","1230":"1230","1294":"1294","1182":"1182","1227":"1227","1304":"1304","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1226":"1226","1357":"1357","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","1179":"1179","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1219":"1219","1307":"1307","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Leicester, Leicestershire, England":"Leicester, Leicestershire, England"},"fi":{"1200–1230":"1200–1230","1202–Male":"1202–Kuollut","1203–1330":"1203–1330","1205–1275":"1205–1275","1203–1245":"1203–1245","1220–1294":"1220–1294","1224–1304":"1224–1304","1226–1357":"1226–1357","1227–1307":"1227–1307","1230–1275":"1230–1275","1179–1210":"1179–1210","1182–1215":"1182–1215","1220":"1220","1275":"1275"